Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

This dataset reports flights in the United States, including carriers, arrival and departure delays, and reasons for delays. The goal of this project is to summarize the data by time periods, carriers,airports and understand different factors causing the airline delays and cancellation.

Data Cleaning¶

In [6]:
# convert the numeric values in Cancelled column to categorical (cancelled - not cancelled):

airlines['Cancelled'] = airlines['Cancelled'].replace([1, 0], ['Cancelled', 'Not Cancelled'])
In [7]:
# convert the numeric values in Diverted column to categorical (converted - not converted):
airlines['Diverted'] = airlines['Diverted'].replace([1,0], ['Diverted', 'Not Diverted'])

Using interpolation to fill NAN values :¶

interpolation is used to fill missing values with previous one or two values. and I am going to use it with all columns that have (minutes) values.

In [19]:
df['departure_time'] = df['departure_time'].interpolate(method='linear', limit_direction='both', axis=0) 
df['arrival_time'] = df['arrival_time'].interpolate(method='linear', limit_direction='both', axis=0)

df['actual_elapsed_time'] = df['actual_elapsed_time'].interpolate(method='linear', limit_direction='both', axis=0) 
df['scheduled_elapsed_time'] = df['scheduled_elapsed_time'].interpolate(method='linear', limit_direction='both', axis=0) 

df['air_time'] = df['air_time'].interpolate(method='linear', limit_direction='both', axis=0) 
df['arrival_delay'] = df['arrival_delay'].interpolate(method='linear', limit_direction='both', axis=0) 

df['departure_delay'] = df['departure_delay'].interpolate(method='linear', limit_direction='both', axis=0) 
df['taxi_in'] = df['taxi_in'].interpolate(method='linear', limit_direction='both', axis=0) 

df['taxi_out'] = df['taxi_out'].interpolate(method='linear', limit_direction='both', axis=0) 
df['carrier_delay'] = df['carrier_delay'].interpolate(method='linear', limit_direction='both', axis=0) 

df['weather_delay'] = df['weather_delay'].interpolate(method='linear', limit_direction='both', axis=0) 
df['NAS_delay'] = df['NAS_delay'].interpolate(method='linear', limit_direction='both', axis=0) 

df['security_delay'] = df['security_delay'].interpolate(method='linear', limit_direction='both', axis=0) 
df['late_aircraft_delay'] = df['late_aircraft_delay'].interpolate(method='linear', limit_direction='both', axis=0)

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Univariate Exploration¶

In univariate analysis, there is only one dependable variable in a dataset, it explores each variable separately. It is possible for two kinds of variables- Categorical and Numerical.

First : Univariate Distribution of Numerical Variables¶

In [22]:
# we will work on sample for quick render and results
samples = np.random.choice(df.shape[0], 200000, replace=False)
airline_samp = df.loc[samples, :]
In [23]:
airline_cancelled = airline_samp.query("cancelled == 'Cancelled'")
airline_notcancelled = airline_samp.query("cancelled == 'Not Cancelled'")

In [25]:
# create subplot
fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(ncols=2, figsize=[18, 6])

# box plot 
a = sns.boxplot(data = airline_notcancelled , x = 'distance', color = blue, ax = ax1)
a.set_xlabel(xlabel= 'Distance', size = 10, weight = 'bold')
a.set(xlim=(-10, 3000))

# histogram
a = sns.histplot(data = airline_notcancelled, x = 'distance', kde = True, bins= 50, color = blue, ax = ax2)
a.set_xlabel(xlabel = 'Distance' , size = 10, weight = 'bold')
a.set(xlim=(-10, 3000))

# draw mean distance line in the histogram plot
mean = airline_notcancelled.distance.mean()
plt.axvline(x = mean, color = red, linestyle = '--', label = 'mean_distance')

# add title
plt.suptitle("Distribution of the Distance of the flight that are not cancelled", weight='bold', size=14)

plt.legend()
plt.show()
  • The histogram is skewied to the right with mean distance around 750 miles.
  • The most flights that are not cancelled is less than 1000 miles in distance.

lets see the distrbution of distance with airlines that are cancelled¶

fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(ncols=2, figsize=(18, 6))

ax2.set_title('Diverted Vs. Not Diverted (%)')
p1= airline_samp.diverted.value_counts(normalize=True).plot.bar(color=blue, width=0.9, ax=ax2)


plt.legend()
plt.show()

It seems that less than 5% of this data is cancelled, and almost zero is diverted.

In [34]:
plt.figure(figsize=[16, 6])

# Plot
order = airline_cancelled['cancellation_code'].value_counts().index
g = sns.countplot(data=airline_cancelled, x='cancellation_code', color=blue, order=order)

# writing the ration over the bars 
for bar in range(airline_cancelled['cancellation_code'].value_counts().shape[0]):
    count = airline_cancelled['cancellation_code'].value_counts()[bar]
    pct = (airline_cancelled['cancellation_code'].value_counts()[bar]/\
    airline_cancelled['cancellation_code'].shape[0])
    pct = (round(pct, 5)*100).round(2)
    plt.text(x=bar, y=count, s= f" {pct}%", va='top', ha='center', fontsize = 10)

    
# rename the columns
g.set_xticklabels(['Weather', 'Carrier', 'NAS'])

# axes labels
plt.xlabel('Cancellation Reason', fontsize = 10, weight = "bold")
plt.ylabel('Count', fontsize = 10, weight = "bold")

# title
plt.title('Cancellation Reasons %', weight='bold', size=14)

plt.show()

The most two reasons that affect the cancellation process are Weather and Carrier and then the National Air System. And the security dont have affect on the cancellation process

Bivariate Exploration¶

Bivariate Exploration : visualizations involving two variables. We use bivariate visualizations to look at relationships. The variation in one variable will affect the value of the other variable.

In [38]:
# correlation matrix

plt.figure(figsize=(20, 18))

sns.heatmap(airline_notcancelled.corr(), square=True, annot=True, fmt='.2f', cmap= 'PuRd', center=.3, linewidth=1, annot_kws={'fontsize': 10});

plt.title("Correlation Matrix", size=14, weight="bold", y = 1.1)

plt.show()

  • Distance is highly correlated with actual elapased time 96% , scheduled elapsed time 98% and air time 98% and this makes a huge sense because the more the distance is the more the time you will spend in the air.

  • Arrival delay is highly correlated with the Departure delay 93%, and this also makes sense because the flights that arrived delay most likely would departure delay.

Conclusions¶

  • American Eagel Airlines and American Airlines were the most cancelled flights.
  • The most cancelletion flights were because of the Weather and Carrier.
  • Cancelled and Delayed Flights more happened in February, December, January and March, and more happened during the day of week.
  • Arrival Delay with Departure Delay were highly correlated 93%.
  • Distance with Actual Elapsed Time and Air Time were highly correlated (96% - 98%).
  • The short Distance for both cancelled and delayed flights were more likely to happened more than the long distance.
  • Northwest Airlines has the most delayed flights followed by American Eagel Airlines and American Airlines.

suggestions If you want to book a flight form the above analysis I can say :

  • Travel in the weekends the least cancellation and delayed flights.
  • Travel in the summer months beacause the bad weather is very strong feature that affect the cancellation.
  • If you want to travel with these Airlines NW , AA , MQ avoid the flights with short distance.
